**Tests (deterministic, temp repo + Writer harness):**
- Pin-set correctness: eval ArtifactSource keeps its target run pinned; a
  replay_of stage keeps its source run pinned; a run pinned by both appears once.
- Report (default, no --prune): TOTAL bytes accurate; OVERSIZED at the
  --max-size boundary (just-over vs just-under); EXTERNAL lists pointer
  artifacts; empty store -> "nothing to report"; default NEVER deletes (assert
  all refs still present).
- Prune: `--prune <leaf-run>` deletes only that ref (others survive); `--prune`
  of an EVAL-PINNED run is REFUSED (run survives, reason printed); `--prune` of
  a REPLAY_OF-SOURCE run is REFUSED; unknown run id -> refused/error; `--prune`
  with no args -> error.
- DeleteRef: deletes an existing ref; errors on missing / symbolic / out-of-
  namespace ref.
- CLI: registration + --help; multiple run ids; mixed prunable+refused batch
  (prunes the ok ones, refuses the pinned ones, clear exit semantics).

**Docs:** Add docs/gc.md (dry-run-default report; --prune <run-id> explicit
delete + safety invariant; "object cleanup is `git gc`'s job"; no auto-collect)
and index it in docs/README.md. Update top-level README if it lists commands.

**Scope / deferred (stated):** NO auto-collection of unreachable runs (none
exist — leaf runs are kept work); tree-rewriting (orphan blobs impossible);
invoking `git gc`; external-URI liveness/deletion; eval pruning; retro
namespace; age-based retention. v1 = report + explicit safe targeted prune.

**Why this resolves the prior contradiction:** earlier drafts defined an auto-
collected "unreachable run" category, but "unreachable" (no inbound edge) = a
normal leaf run = kept work, so auto-collecting it would delete the user's data.
v1 removes auto-collection entirely: gc only deletes runs the user NAMES, and
only when the safety invariant permits.

